Determining Risk Factors for Injuries and Fatalities in Road Collisions

Introduction

The Canadian National Collision Database contains information on all police-reported motor vehicle collisions over many years. The attached dataset 2019_dataset_en.csv contains such information for 272301 collisions in the year 2019.

This R Notebook will load this dataset, clean, inspect and visualize its contents, and produce a machine learning model to predict the severity of a collision (whether it resulted in no injuries, non-fatal, or fatal injuries) given a subset of the other available information.

Loading the dataset

The dataset will be loaded as a CSV into the active R environment, it must be located in the same directory as this R Notebook:

data <- read_csv("2019_dataset_en.csv", show_col_types = FALSE)

Cleaning the data

To clean the data, six columns containing unique identifiers, the year (2019), and other variables not relevant or inhibitory to this machine learning task must be removed as follows:

data <- data %>%
  select(-c(C_YEAR, C_SEV, V_ID, P_ID, P_SAFE, C_CASE))

For the meanings of these column names, refer to the attached data_dictionary.pdf for details.

The remaining columns are almost exclusively categorical variables, and contain categories for unknown and missing data. These must be removed for the machine learning model to process the dataset.

data <- data %>%
  filter(C_MNTH!="UU",C_MNTH!="XX") %>%
  filter(C_WDAY!="U") %>% 
  filter(C_HOUR!="UU") %>%
  filter(C_VEHS!="UU",C_VEHS!="XX") %>%
  filter(C_CONF!="QQ",C_CONF!="UU",C_CONF!="XX") %>%
  filter(C_RCFG!="QQ",C_RCFG!="UU",C_RCFG!="XX") %>% 
  filter(C_WTHR!="U",C_WTHR!="X",C_WTHR!="Q") %>% 
  filter(C_RSUR!="U",C_RSUR!="X",C_RSUR!="Q") %>%
  filter(C_RALN!="U",C_RALN!="X",C_RALN!="Q") %>%
  filter(C_TRAF!="QQ",C_TRAF!="UU",C_TRAF!="XX") %>%
  filter(V_TYPE!="NN",V_TYPE!="QQ",V_TYPE!="UU",V_TYPE!="XX") %>%
  filter(V_YEAR!="NNNN",V_YEAR!="UUUU",V_YEAR!="XXXX") %>%
  filter(P_SEX!="N",P_SEX!="U",P_SEX!="X") %>%
  filter(P_AGE!="NN",P_AGE!="UU",P_AGE!="XX") %>%
  filter(P_PSN!="NN",P_PSN!="QQ",P_PSN!="UU",P_PSN!="XX") %>%
  filter(P_USER!="U") %>%
  filter(P_ISEV!="N",P_ISEV!="U")

Removing these leaves 17 of the original 23 columns and 167803 of the original 272301 observations. Finally, the most of remaining data must be converted to factors / categorical variables, and some variables will be grouped into fewer categories than they began with.

# Group the C_CONF column while naming categories.
data <- data %>%
  mutate(C_CONF = (ifelse(data$C_CONF <= 10, 'Single Vehicle',
                    ifelse(data$C_CONF>20 & data$C_CONF <30, '2 Vehicles',
                    ifelse(data$C_CONF>30 & data$C_CONF<40,'2 Vehicles Head On','2 Vehicles Parked')))))

# Convert most variables to factors and some to numeric.
data$C_MNTH <- as.factor(data$C_MNTH)
data$C_WDAY <- as.factor(data$C_WDAY)
data$C_HOUR <- as.numeric(data$C_HOUR)
data$C_VEHS <- as.numeric(data$C_VEHS)
data$C_CONF <- as.factor(data$C_CONF)
data$C_RCFG <- as.factor(data$C_RCFG)
data$C_WTHR <- as.factor(data$C_WTHR)
data$C_RSUR <- as.factor(data$C_RSUR)
data$C_RALN <- as.factor(data$C_RALN)
data$C_TRAF <- as.factor(data$C_TRAF)
data$V_TYPE <- as.factor(data$V_TYPE)
data$V_YEAR <- as.numeric(data$V_YEAR)
data$P_SEX <- as.factor(data$P_SEX)
data$P_AGE <- as.numeric(data$P_AGE)
data$P_PSN <- as.factor(data$P_PSN)
data$P_ISEV <- as.factor(data$P_ISEV)
data$P_USER <- as.factor(data$P_USER)

First, we create bar charts to see how many collisions of each severity there are according to each variable. Most of the variables are either categorical, or integer numbers so bar charts are the best option.

Bar charts are displayed grouped by theme:

  • Time
  • Demographics
  • Weather & road conditions
  • Vehicle info
  • Road info
  • Driver/passenger info
  • Collision info

Note that for all variables, the amount of fatalities is drastically lower than the amount of injuries and non-injuries, to the point where its impossible to view patterns in the data. Therefore, for each varaible there is a separate chart to show how fatalities correlate with each variable.

#Display similar grouped histograms:

#Histograms for time/day/month
timeHists <- (monthHist|weekdayHist|hourHist) & theme(legend.position = "right")
timeHistsFatal <- (monthHistFatal|weekdayHistFatal|hourHistFatal) & theme(legend.position = "none")
